<h2>
    Effective Salmon Tactics for Lakes
</h2>
<ol>
    <li>
        <strong>Trolling</strong>: rig flashers with spoons or corn flies—ideal above deeper breaks.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Vertical Jigging</strong>: tip jigs with roe or beads near thermocline layers.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Time It Right</strong>: early summer mornings yield best kokanee activity.
    </li>
</ol>
<h2>
    River Salmon Fishing Techniques
</h2>
<ol>
    <li>
        <strong>Float Fishing</strong>: bobbers with roe or sand shrimp below Sherar’s.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Plug/Bobbing</strong>: drift plugs in eddies on shallow tailouts.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Spin Lures</strong>: spinners like Blue Fox, Mepps attract Chinook and Coho.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Pay Attention</strong> to posted open/closed sections—check ODFW.
    </li>
</ol>
<h2>
    Gear &amp; Setup
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Rod</strong>: 7–9 ft medium-heavy spinning or baitcasting for lakes; 10–12 ft for rivers.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Line</strong>: 10–20 lb braid with 10–15 lb fluoro or mono leader.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Tackle</strong>: flashers, spinners, spoons, roe bags, 2–4 oz sinkers.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Boater Essentials</strong>: depth/fish finder, safety gear, PFD, permits.
    </li>
</ul>
